reconstruct the history of South Asian Tantra from the medieval period to the present day. Kiss of the Yogini focuses on what White identifies as the sole truly distinctive feature of South Asian Tantra: sexualized ritual practices, especially as expressed in the medieval Kaula rites. Such practices centered on the exchange of powerful, transformative sexual fluids between male practitioners and wild female bird and animal spirits known as Yoginis. It was only by "drinking" the sexual fluids of the Yoginis that men could enter the family of the supreme godhead and thereby obtain supernatural powers and transform themselves into gods. By focusing on sexual rituals, White resituates South Asian Tantra, in its precolonial form, at the center of religious, social, and political life, arguing that Tantra was the mainstream, and that in many ways it continues to influence contemporary Hinduism, even if reformist misunderstandings relegate it to a marginal position. Kiss of the Yogini contains White's own translations from over a dozen Tantras that have never before been translated into any European language. It will prove to be the definitive work for persons seeking to understand Tantra and the crucial role it has played in South Asian history, society, culture, and religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSexxReligious aspectsxTantrism. 0aTantrismzSouth Asia. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  atantric sex, sexuality, cultural appropriation, ritual, ceremony, south asia, religion, spirituality, tantra, kaula, rites, yoginis, transformation, spirits, animal, supernatural, gods, divinity, spiritual growth, colonialism, hinduism, hindu, demonesses, goddesses, witches, femininity, nonfiction, gender, cults, siddha, tradition, folk belief, folklore.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Pr